On World Humanitarian Day, this article pays tribute to humanitarian workers and emphasizes the importance of putting human rights at the center of foreign policy. It highlights the current global need for humanitarian assistance and protection, with over 235 million people in 56 countries requiring aid. The challenges faced by aid workers include political repression, armed conflict, gender-based violence, natural disasters, the COVID-19 pandemic, and climate change. Despite these challenges, aid workers demonstrate courage, commitment, and a drive to help others in need. The article condemns attacks against humanitarian aid workers and recognizes the efforts of health workers on the front lines of the pandemic. It also mentions specific regions where aid workers are providing critical services, including Afghanistan, Mozambique, Burma, Venezuela, Ethiopia, and conflict-afflicted areas. The article concludes by expressing solidarity with aid workers and their dedication to saving lives, preserving human dignity, and alleviating suffering.